The key design decision is using a `Tool` trait with `Arc<dyn Tool>` for dynamic dispatch, stored in a `HashMap<String, Arc<dyn Tool>>`. This gives us runtime extensibility (plugins can register tools) while keeping the registry thread-safe via `Arc`.

```rust
use anyhow::Result;
use serde_json::Value;
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::pin::Pin;
use std::future::Future;
use std::sync::Arc;
use tokio::sync::watch;

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct ToolResult {
    pub output: String,
    pub is_error: bool,
}

impl ToolResult {
    pub fn success(output: impl Into<String>) -> Self {
        Self { output: output.into(), is_error: false }
    }
    pub fn error(output: impl Into<String>) -> Self {
        Self { output: output.into(), is_error: true }
    }
}

pub struct CancelToken {
    sender: watch::Sender<bool>,
    receiver: watch::Receiver<bool>,
}

impl CancelToken {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        let (sender, receiver) = watch::channel(false);
        Self { sender, receiver }
    }
    pub fn cancel(&self) { self.sender.send(true).ok(); }
    pub fn is_cancelled(&self) -> bool { *self.receiver.borrow() }
}

pub struct ToolContext {
    pub cwd: std::path::PathBuf,
    pub project_path: std::path::PathBuf,
}

pub trait Tool: Send + Sync {
    fn name(&self) -> &str;
    fn description(&self) -> &str;
    fn parameters(&self) -> Value;
    fn execute(&self, params: Value, ctx: &ToolContext)
        -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = Result<ToolResult>> + Send + '_>>;
    fn execute_with_cancel(&self, params: Value, ctx: &ToolContext,
        _cancel: &CancelToken, _progress: Option<tokio::sync::mpsc::Sender<String>>)
        -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = Result<ToolResult>> + Send + '_>> {
        self.execute(params, ctx)
    }
}

pub struct ToolRegistry {
    tools: HashMap<String, Arc<dyn Tool>>,
}

impl ToolRegistry {
    pub fn new() -> Self { Self { tools: HashMap::new() } }
    pub fn register(&mut self, tool: impl Tool + 'static) {
        let name = tool.name().to_string();
        self.tools.insert(name, Arc::new(tool));
    }
    pub fn get(&self, name: &str) -> Option<Arc<dyn Tool>> {
        self.tools.get(name).cloned()
    }
    pub async fn execute(&self, name: &str, params: Value, ctx: &ToolContext) -> Result<ToolResult> {
        let tool = self.tools.get(name)
            .ok_or_else(|| anyhow::anyhow!("Unknown tool: {name}"))?;
        tool.execute(params, ctx).await
    }
}
```

Key decisions: (1) `execute_with_cancel` has a default impl that delegates to `execute` so existing tools don't need to implement cancellation. (2) `ToolResult` uses `is_error` flag instead of `Result` because tool errors are data for the model, not panics. (3) `CancelToken` uses `watch::channel` for zero-overhead polling.

Use a static classification function rather than a trait method. This keeps the concurrency decision centralized and avoids requiring every tool implementation to self-report (which they could get wrong).

```rust
impl ToolRegistry {
    /// Returns true if this tool is read-only (safe for concurrent execution).
    pub fn is_read_only(tool_name: &str) -> bool {
        matches!(
            tool_name,
            "file_read" | "grep" | "glob" | "web_fetch"
                | "ask_user" | "memory_read" | "research"
                | "request_permissions"
        )
    }
}
```

Then in your agent loop:
```rust
let tool_calls = parse_tool_calls(&response);
let (read_only, mutating): (Vec<_>, Vec<_>) = tool_calls
    .into_iter()
    .partition(|tc| ToolRegistry::is_read_only(&tc.name));

// Run all read-only tools concurrently
let read_futures: Vec<_> = read_only.iter()
    .map(|tc| registry.execute(&tc.name, tc.params.clone(), &ctx))
    .collect();
let read_results = futures::future::join_all(read_futures).await;

// Run mutating tools serially
for tc in &mutating {
    let result = registry.execute(&tc.name, tc.params.clone(), &ctx).await;
    // handle result
}
```

Why static classification over self-reporting: the registry is the authority on what's safe. A plugin tool that claims to be read-only but runs `rm -rf` would bypass your safety checks. By centralizing it, you also get a single place to audit. Unknown tools default to mutating (safe default).

Add it as a default method on the trait so existing tools get a reasonable fallback without code changes:

```rust
pub trait Tool: Send + Sync {
    fn name(&self) -> &str;
    fn description(&self) -> &str;
    fn parameters(&self) -> Value;
    fn execute(&self, params: Value, ctx: &ToolContext)
        -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = Result<ToolResult>> + Send + '_>>;

    /// Short summary of this tool call for logging/display.
    /// Default: `"tool_name({truncated_args})"` capped at 80 chars.
    fn classify_summary(&self, args: &Value) -> String {
        let s = args.to_string();
        let truncated = if s.len() > 80 {
            format!("{}...", &s[..77])
        } else {
            s
        };
        format!("{}({})", self.name(), truncated)
    }
}
```

Specific tools override this for better UX:
```rust
impl Tool for BashTool {
    fn classify_summary(&self, args: &Value) -> String {
        let cmd = args.get("command")
            .and_then(|v| v.as_str())
            .unwrap_or("(unknown)");
        let preview: String = cmd.chars().take(60).collect();
        format!("bash: {preview}")
    }
}
```

The 80-char truncation prevents the TUI from breaking when models pass large JSON blobs as arguments. The `...` suffix signals to the user that content was clipped.

```rust
use tokio::sync::watch;

/// A cancellation token backed by a `tokio::sync::watch` channel.
/// The owner calls `cancel()` to signal; any holder of a cloned receiver
/// can poll `is_cancelled()` without overhead.
#[derive(Debug)]
pub struct CancelToken {
    sender: watch::Sender<bool>,
    receiver: watch::Receiver<bool>,
}

impl CancelToken {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        let (sender, receiver) = watch::channel(false);
        Self { sender, receiver }
    }

    /// Signal cancellation. Idempotent.
    pub fn cancel(&self) {
        self.sender.send(true).ok();
    }

    /// Check whether cancellation has been requested.
    pub fn is_cancelled(&self) -> bool {
        *self.receiver.borrow()
    }

    /// Clone the receiver half so another task can observe the signal.
    pub fn clone_receiver(&self) -> watch::Receiver<bool> {
        self.receiver.clone()
    }
}

impl Default for CancelToken {
    fn default() -> Self { Self::new() }
}
```

Usage inside a tool that shells out:
```rust
fn execute_with_cancel(&self, params: Value, ctx: &ToolContext,
    cancel: &CancelToken, progress: Option<mpsc::Sender<ToolProgress>>)
    -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = Result<ToolResult>> + Send + '_>> {
    Box::pin(async move {
        let mut child = tokio::process::Command::new("bash")
            .arg("-c").arg(&command).spawn()?;
        let mut rx = cancel.clone_receiver();
        tokio::select! {
            status = child.wait() => {
                // Normal completion
                Ok(ToolResult::success(output))
            }
            _ = rx.changed() => {
                child.kill().await.ok();
                Ok(ToolResult::error("Cancelled"))
            }
        }
    })
}
```

Why `watch` over `oneshot`: watch supports multiple receivers and repeated polling without consuming the channel. A bash tool spawns a child process in a separate task that needs its own receiver clone.

```rust
impl ToolRegistry {
    /// Create registry with all default tools
    pub fn with_defaults() -> Self {
        let mut reg = Self::new();
        reg.register(BashTool::new());
        reg.register(FileReadTool);
        reg.register(FileWriteTool);
        reg.register(FileEditTool);
        reg.register(GlobTool);
        reg.register(GrepTool);
        reg.register(GitTool);
        reg.register(WebFetchTool);
        reg.register(AskUserTool);
        reg.register(RequestPermissionsTool);
        reg.register(MemoryReadTool);
        reg.register(MemoryWriteTool);
        reg.register(AgentSpawnTool);
        reg.register(TaskTool);
        reg.register(ResearchTool);
        reg
    }

    /// Register multiple plugin tools at once.
    pub fn register_plugin_tools(&mut self, tools: Vec<impl Tool + 'static>) {
        for tool in tools {
            self.register(tool);
        }
    }
}
```

Plugin tools are namespaced to prevent collisions with builtins:
```rust
// In PluginManager::get_tools()
PluginTool::new(
    format!("plugin:{}:{}", plugin.manifest.plugin.name, tool_def.name),
    tool_def.description.clone(),
    tool_def.command.clone(),
    plugin.dir.clone(),
    tool_def.params.clone(),
)
```

The `plugin:` prefix is critical for security: it means a plugin can never masquerade as a built-in tool like `bash` or `file_write`. The permission classifier sees the full namespaced name, so plugin tools go through the same permission pipeline as everything else.

