The core is a `classify` function that returns a tier, plus a `hard_block_check` for commands that are never allowed regardless of user preferences:

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub enum PermissionTier { Safe, Write, Destructive }

#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub enum PermissionVerdict { Approved, NeedsConfirmation(String), Blocked(String) }

pub fn hard_block_check(tool_name: &str, params: &Value) -> Option<String> {
    match tool_name {
        "bash" => {
            let cmd = params.get("command").and_then(|v| v.as_str()).unwrap_or("");
            let normalized = cmd.split_whitespace().collect::<Vec<_>>().join(" ");
            for blocked in HARD_BLOCKED_COMMANDS {
                if normalized.contains(blocked) {
                    return Some(format!("Hard-blocked: {blocked}"));
                }
            }
            None
        }
        "file_write" | "file_edit" => {
            let path = params.get("path").and_then(|v| v.as_str()).unwrap_or("");
            for prefix in HARD_BLOCKED_PATH_PREFIXES {
                if path.starts_with(prefix) {
                    return Some(format!("Hard-blocked path: {prefix}"));
                }
            }
            None
        }
        _ => None,
    }
}

pub fn classify(tool_name: &str, params: &Value) -> PermissionTier {
    match tool_name {
        "file_read" | "glob" | "grep" | "web_fetch" | "ask_user" => PermissionTier::Safe,
        "file_write" | "file_edit" => PermissionTier::Write,
        "git" => classify_git(params),
        "bash" => classify_bash(params),
        _ => PermissionTier::Write, // unknown defaults to Write
    }
}

fn classify_bash(params: &Value) -> PermissionTier {
    let command = params.get("command").and_then(|v| v.as_str()).unwrap_or("");
    let segments = split_compound_command(command);
    let mut worst = PermissionTier::Safe;
    for segment in &segments {
        worst = worse_tier(worst, classify_single_bash(segment));
    }
    worst
}
```

Key design decisions:
- Hard blocks are separate from classification. `rm -rf /` is blocked even in YOLO mode.
- Compound commands (`ls && rm file`) are split and classified by worst segment.
- Subshell wrappers (`$(rm file)`, backtick-rm-backtick) are stripped before classification.
- Unknown tools default to Write (fail-safe), not Safe.

Split compound commands on `&&`, `||`, `;`, and `|`, respecting quotes, then classify each segment independently. The final tier is the worst of all segments:

```rust
fn split_compound_command(cmd: &str) -> Vec<String> {
    let mut segments = Vec::new();
    let mut current = String::new();
    let mut chars = cmd.chars().peekable();
    let mut in_single_quote = false;
    let mut in_double_quote = false;

    while let Some(c) = chars.next() {
        match c {
            '\'' if !in_double_quote => {
                in_single_quote = !in_single_quote;
                current.push(c);
            }
            '"' if !in_single_quote => {
                in_double_quote = !in_double_quote;
                current.push(c);
            }
            '&' if !in_single_quote && !in_double_quote => {
                if chars.peek() == Some(&'&') {
                    chars.next();
                    segments.push(current.clone());
                    current.clear();
                } else {
                    current.push(c);
                }
            }
            '|' if !in_single_quote && !in_double_quote => {
                if chars.peek() == Some(&'|') { chars.next(); }
                segments.push(current.clone());
                current.clear();
            }
            ';' if !in_single_quote && !in_double_quote => {
                segments.push(current.clone());
                current.clear();
            }
            _ => current.push(c),
        }
    }
    if !current.trim().is_empty() { segments.push(current); }
    segments
}

fn worse_tier(a: PermissionTier, b: PermissionTier) -> PermissionTier {
    match (a, b) {
        (PermissionTier::Destructive, _) | (_, PermissionTier::Destructive) => PermissionTier::Destructive,
        (PermissionTier::Write, _) | (_, PermissionTier::Write) => PermissionTier::Write,
        _ => PermissionTier::Safe,
    }
}
```

So `ls | grep foo` splits to [`ls`, `grep foo`] -> both Safe -> Safe.
`ls && rm file.txt` splits to [`ls`, `rm file.txt`] -> Safe + Destructive -> Destructive.

The quote tracking prevents splitting inside string arguments like `echo "hello && world"`.

```rust
/// Strip subshell wrappers like $(...), `...`, (...) from command start.
fn strip_subshell(cmd: &str) -> &str {
    let trimmed = cmd.trim();
    if let Some(inner) = trimmed.strip_prefix("$(") {
        if let Some(stripped) = inner.strip_suffix(')') {
            return stripped.trim();
        }
    }
    if let Some(inner) = trimmed.strip_prefix('`') {
        if let Some(stripped) = inner.strip_suffix('`') {
            return stripped.trim();
        }
    }
    if let Some(inner) = trimmed.strip_prefix('(') {
        if let Some(stripped) = inner.strip_suffix(')') {
            return stripped.trim();
        }
    }
    trimmed
}

fn classify_single_bash(cmd: &str) -> PermissionTier {
    let trimmed = cmd.trim();
    let inner = strip_subshell(trimmed);

    // Check destructive patterns on the inner command
    for pattern in DESTRUCTIVE_BASH_PATTERNS {
        if inner.starts_with(pattern) || inner.contains(&format!(" {pattern}")) {
            return PermissionTier::Destructive;
        }
    }

    // Check system path access in write commands
    let first_word = inner.split_whitespace().next().unwrap_or("");
    if matches!(first_word, "tee" | "cp" | "mv" | "mkdir" | "touch") {
        for prefix in SYSTEM_PATH_PREFIXES {
            if inner.contains(prefix) {
                return PermissionTier::Destructive;
            }
        }
    }

    // Safe commands
    for safe in SAFE_BASH_COMMANDS {
        if inner == *safe || inner.starts_with(&format!("{safe} ")) {
            return PermissionTier::Safe;
        }
    }

    PermissionTier::Write // default for unknown
}
```

Test:
```rust
assert_eq!(classify("bash", &json!({"command": "$(rm file.txt)"})), PermissionTier::Destructive);
assert_eq!(classify("bash", &json!({"command": "`rm file.txt`"})), PermissionTier::Destructive);
```

The stripping is one level deep by design. Deeply nested subshells like `$($(rm))` are edge cases that the hard_block_check catches via pattern matching on the raw string.

