Layer it as: hard block check -> classify tier -> check against permission mode and grant cache.

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub enum PermissionTier { Safe, Write, Destructive }

#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub enum PermissionVerdict { Approved, NeedsConfirmation(String), Blocked(String) }

pub fn check_permission(
    tier: PermissionTier,
    mode: &PermissionMode,
    grant_cache: &GrantCache,
    tool_name: &str,
    params: &Value,
) -> PermissionVerdict {
    match tier {
        PermissionTier::Safe => PermissionVerdict::Approved,
        PermissionTier::Write => match mode {
            PermissionMode::Ask => {
                if grant_cache.matches(tool_name, params) {
                    PermissionVerdict::Approved
                } else {
                    PermissionVerdict::NeedsConfirmation(describe_action(tool_name, params))
                }
            }
            PermissionMode::Auto | PermissionMode::Yolo => PermissionVerdict::Approved,
        },
        PermissionTier::Destructive => {
            // ALWAYS requires confirmation, regardless of mode.
            // Grant cache never covers destructive actions.
            PermissionVerdict::NeedsConfirmation(describe_action(tool_name, params))
        }
    }
}
```

Three permission modes: Ask (prompt for writes), Auto (auto-approve writes, prompt for destructive), Yolo (auto-approve writes, still prompt for destructive). Destructive always prompts.

The hard block check runs first and returns `Blocked` unconditionally for things like `rm -rf /` or writing to `/etc/passwd`.

Split compound commands on shell operators, classify each segment, take the worst:

```rust
fn classify_bash(params: &Value) -> PermissionTier {
    let command = params.get("command").and_then(|v| v.as_str()).unwrap_or("");
    let segments = split_compound_command(command);
    let mut worst = PermissionTier::Safe;
    for segment in &segments {
        let tier = classify_single_bash(segment);
        worst = worse_tier(worst, tier);
    }
    worst
}
```

`split_compound_command` handles `&&`, `||`, `;`, and `|` while respecting single and double quotes. So `echo "hello && world"` stays as one segment.

Each segment goes through:
1. Strip subshell wrappers: `$(...)`, backticks, `(...)`
2. Check destructive patterns: `rm`, `sudo`, `kill`, `chmod 777`
3. Check system path access in write commands
4. Check safe command list: `ls`, `cat`, `grep`, `cargo test`, etc.
5. Default: Write

For your example: `ls -la && rm -rf /tmp/stuff` -> [`ls -la`, `rm -rf /tmp/stuff`] -> Safe + Destructive -> Destructive. The user gets prompted before execution.

